As Professor in layden he had the full use of the two Vossian mss. there, the main foundation of a genuine text: how did he use this advantage, which in profession he makes so much ofl The chief feature of his edition is a vast and cumbrous apparatus of various readings, derived 'from about thirtyone sources professedly distinct. So incredibly careless is he, that the Vossian collatioris which he borrows from Tonson are or should be those of his Leyden mss: see note 1 to v 471 for a glaring instance of a false reading which he slavishly copies from Tonson and ascribes to his Leyden quarto. His various readings are therefore not only cumbrously inane, but are a snare and delusion, and have led astray those who like Wakefield have trusted to them. Thus in his hands the two un- rivalled Leyden mss. have been worse than useless.
